				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Battle for Club Med Heats Up as Chinese and French Investors Increase Bid</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By David Jolly			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-09-12T11:37:12+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">September 12, 2014 7:37 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">September 12, 2014 7:37 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/09/12/battle-for-club-med-heats-up-as-chinese-and-french-investors-increase-bid/" data-title="Battle for Club Med Heats Up as Chinese and French Investors Increase Bid" data-description="Fosun International, a giant Chinese financial and industrial conglomerate, and its French partner, Ardian, increased their bid to about $1.1 billion to counter an Italian group&#039;s offer.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/12/business/dealbook/dbpix-clubmed/dbpix-clubmed-blog480-v2.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/12/business/dealbook/dbpix-clubmed/dbpix-clubmed-blog480-v2.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/12/business/dealbook/dbpix-clubmed/dbpix-clubmed-blog480-v2.jpg" id="100000003110041" width="480" height="360" alt="Club Med&#039;s management is backing the latest offer."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="360"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Club Med's management is backing the latest offer.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> John Schults/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">PARIS â The battle for Club MÃ©diterranÃ©e took a sharp last-minute turn on Friday when the Chinese and French investors who had originally sought to buy the vacation resort operator came back with an improved counteroffer just before the deadline for action.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Fosun International, a giant Chinese financial and industrial conglomerate, and its French partner, Ardian, said they were offering 22 euros for each share of the vacation resort group, valuing the company at â¬839 million, or about $1.1 billion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That offer, backed by Club Med&#8217;s management, represents a 4.8 percent premium to the bid of â¬21 a share made in June by Andrea C. Bonomi, senior partner of the Italian group Investindustrial.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The winner of the battle will set the strategy for a company that has come to define the package vacation experience for people around the world, and provide the company with the funding it needs to reach untapped markets and maintain its position where it is already established.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Club Med&#8217;s chief executive, Henri Giscard dâEstaing, had said last year that he would work with Ardian and Fosun to double the number of Chinese guests, while the Italian group had stressed the need for expansion in Europe and Latin America.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After the new bid on Friday, however, both camps have begun to sound quite similar about their plans. Indeed, Mr. Bonomi has said that he would welcome Fosun as a partner.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The new bid, which includes Club Med&#8217;s convertible bonds, was made through the French and Chinese companies&#8217; Gaillon Invest II consortium. It came just hours before a deadline imposed by French market rules for the companies to put up or go home.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;We are presenting the highest offer for Club MÃ©diterranÃ©e, and the best liquidity for all the company&#8217;s shareholders,â Jiannong Qian, the head of the Gaillon Invest, said in a statement. âThis plan is a guarantee of stability for Club MÃ©diterranÃ©e and its future development.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Shares of Club Med, which last traded at â¬21.27, were suspended earlier on Friday at the order of the French market regulator. They are to begin trading again Monday.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Aârdian sold its entire 9 percent stake âin Club Med âto Fosun on Friday morning at the â¬22 offer price, âEstelle Guillot-Tantay, a spokeswoman for Ardian, saidâ.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While that gives âFosun âfull control of the bid, she said, Ardian has committed to invest â¬20 million in the company if the deal goes through.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Fosun and its allies âcurrently holdâ â18.3 percent of the shares and 24.4 percent of the voting rights in Club Med; the offer is contingent on their obtaining more than 50 percent.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A Club Med spokeswoman, Caroline Bruel, did not immediately respond to a request for comment.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The new offer must now be vetted by a committee of the market regulator, which will set a new closing date for the competing offers.â StÃ©fanie Duschenes, a spokeswoman for the regulator, declined to comment.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe&#8217;ve noted the increased offer by Fosun,â David Sturkin, a spokesman for Mr. Bonomi said, âand in line with French takeover rules we&#8217;re going to take our time looking at our options.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The new bid includes a dominant role for Fosun, as the Chinese company holds 85.1 percent of Gaillon Invest II. The remainder is split among Ardian; U-Tour, a Shanghai-listed travel company that Club Med works with in China; and Club Med&#8217;s management. Fidelidade, a Portuguese insurer controlled by Fosun, is also involved in the bid.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">To allay concerns that the deal backed by the Chinese investors would dilute Club Med&#8217;s European image, the companies said that Club Med&#8217;s headquarters would remain in Paris and that its shares would continue to be listed on the Paris bourse. Mr. Giscard dâEstaing would remain as chairman and chief executive.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ardian, formerly known as Axa Private Equity, and Fosun had appeared to have the deal sewn up last year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">They announced in May 2013 that they would take the company private and speed up the roll-out of new clubs in developing markets like China to restore growth to a company that has been hurt by the stagnating European economy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">They later sweetened their initial â¬17 a share offer to â¬17.50 a share to lure holdout stockholders.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But in June Mr. Bonomi unveiled his <a title="Italian group competing bid for club med" href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/30/hostile-bid-for-club-med-threatens-existing-deal/ ">hostile bid</a>, offering 22 percent more money than had the French and Chinese partners.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Bonomi argued that the partners and Club Med was placing too much emphasis on China, and said he planned to more aggressively invest in Europe and Latin America, in addition to Asia.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In their statement on Friday, the Chinese and French bidders underlined that their own strategy was not dissimilar to Mr. Bonomi&#8217;s, saying the new offer âwill reinforce Club Medâs strategy of gaining market shares in mature markets, especially in France, and accelerating growth in fast developing markets,â including in China, Brazil, Russia and Southeast Asia.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Bonomi is working through an ad hoc consortium called Global Resorts that his Investindustrial controls. The other members of his group are Sol Kerzner, a South African hotelier; the PortAventura amusement park group; and GP Investments, a Latin American private equity firm.</p>
	</div>
